Virgo is an easy-to-use open-source spectrometer and radiometer based on Python and GNU Radio that is conveniently applicable to any radio telescope working with a GR-supported software-defined radio (SDR).
Virgo tackles this problem by providing non-experts with a tool to collect and interpret data from radio telescopes, without requiring expertise in digital signal processing and software engineering.

This is the official repository for ``21cmFAST``: a semi-numerical code that is able to produce 3D cosmological realisations of many physical fields in the early Universe.

``21cmFAST`` has been widely used, for example, by the Murchison Widefield Array (MWA), LOw-Frequency ARray (LOFAR) and Hydrogen Epoch of Reionization Array (HERA), to model the large-scale cosmological 21-cm signal.

README: fastpli is "a toolbox for polarized light imaging (PLI)" with modules for "designing of nerve fiber models" and "simulation of 3D-Polarized Light Imaging (3D-PLI)".
README installation instructs users to "git clone --recursive https://github.com/3d-pli/fastpli.git" then build/install via "make fastpli" and "pip3 install ." (no package registry mentioned).

The Fiber Architecture Simulation Toolbox for 3D-PLI (fastpli) is a toolbox for polarized light imaging (PLI) with three main purposes: designing nerve fiber models, generating collision free models, and simulating 3D-Polarized Light Imaging.
This project has received funding from the European Unions Horizon 2020 Research and Innovation Programme under Grant Agreement No. 7202070 (Human Brain Project) SGA2.
The project is developed by the fiber architecture group at the Forschungszentrum Jlich.
